Gutach: Even more safety for pedestrians
They are less than 100 meters apart: On Tuesday, the new B33 pedestrian traffic light at the village car park in Gutach was put into operation - within sight of the older city hall traffic light.
Two plants so close to each other: Intention or bullshit?
This question was answered clearly yesterday by the mayor of the expert report.
"The city hall light was installed at that time because it secures the way to school", Eckert explained yesterday.
The traffic light is safe for cyclists, bus passengers and mountain residents.
The plant, which was officially commissioned yesterday, is important for the intersection of Sulzbachweg and Kirchstraße.
We have the museum, two churches, the spa park, the bus stop, a doctor and a bank as well as the traffic flow from the residential area › Grub ‹.
"In view of the high traffic and pedestrian volume, a further traffic light had to be installed to ensure their safety," says Eckert.
This is also confirmed by Peter Arnold from the Landratsamt Offenburg.
"According to current measurements on the B 33, about 12,000 vehicles pass through the municipality of Gutach every day, about ten percent of which are heavy goods vehicles," Arnold emphasizes.
Therefore, the construction of a further traffic light is more than necessary: "Safety comes first here," says Arnold.
Altogether four traffic shows were accomplished, also a roundabout was considered, however because of the narrowness in the crossing area Sulzbachweg / Kirchstraße again rejected.
According to Arnold, everything had been tested before when choosing the location of the traffic light poles: "By means of a transporter loaded with especially long logs, we tested whether these vehicles could leave the Sulzbachweg on the B 33 without buckling the traffic light poles."
The traffic light system itself, which costs around 15,000 Euros, is "the most modern system on the market", Arnold explained.
The system is equipped with coloured LEDs that glow so brightly that the lights can be easily seen by drivers, for example, even when the sun is low.
And it is also economical: the older lighting systems consume around 100 watts, the new ones just eight watts.
There are three lighting systems per direction of travel.
Arnold explained the technology of the new system: It is equipped with two radar sensors.
If the pedestrian presses the traffic light button, the upper radar sensor tests the traffic situation.
If the street is free, there is an immediate green for the pedestrian, if not, it takes about 15 seconds.
Another radar sensor checks whether the green phase for the pedestrian can be completed.
"If a group or handicapped people cross the road, the green phase is extended, so everyone comes safely over the road", Arnold explained.
Of course, the driver has to think about this as a partner and observe the road ahead.
This was not the case yesterday: As soon as the traffic lights for pedestrians showed green, an upper class car rushed through - with bright red.
