A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits into the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record every kilometer traveled and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to overhaul the outdated system of financing U.S. American roads.
The normally rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are in favour of the government being able to use the small boxes to record the kilometres travelled - and possibly also where they have been driven - and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Union (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next ten years.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS.
This is really a must for our country.
“It ’ s nothing we ’ ll use just possibly, ” said Hasan Ikhrata, general manager of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record the miles traveled by all Californian drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, financed by taxes, is failing to pay the US at the pump.
But there is not as much refueling in America as there used to be.
Cars use less fuel.
The government ’ s fuel tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per litre) has not risen for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a cent when fuel prices are high.
"The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, an expert on transport legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most sensible alternative in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
Not surprisingly, urban liberals support the idea, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behavior in a way that reduces congestion and climate-damaging emissions.
The Californian planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the ambitious, statutory goals of the state on climate change.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also said that he sees this as the most viable long-term alternative.
Also the free marketers of the Reason Foundation are taken by the idea to let drivers pay after covered distance.
"This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole," says Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former US transport ministers, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move toward mile-based billing.
Last year, the US Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance, reacting to concerns raised by rural MPs who represent people who often have to travel many miles to work or to the city.
Several states and cities are nevertheless moving in this direction on their own.
Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country ’ s largest experiment, is the most committed.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois tests it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 Coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently studying how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, motorists were skeptical of the idea that the government could follow any of their movements.
"Concerns about Big Brother and such things were a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, Nevada's ACLU warned on their website: "It would be relatively easy to turn tachographs into full-fledged monitoring devices."
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on individuals ’ daily movements.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the kilometers traveled, but not exactly when and where.
This, Khan said, would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some government agencies to create a small startup, True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not start to help states to tax drivers.
Rather, their goal was to establish themselves in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers should pay on the basis of the miles flown.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
"People are more willing to get involved if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose no equipment at all and instead pay a flat rate based on the average miles traveled by all state residents.
Other agencies hope to sell the concept of a suspicious public by providing the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that can also be used to pay parking fees, pay for insurance only for kilometers traveled, and collect real-time speed data from other vehicles to help drivers avoid traffic jams.
"Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the advantages offered by the system," says a city planning document.
Some traffic planners wonder, however, whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials said that Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off charge or annual levy could be imposed on drivers of hybrid cars or other low-gasoline vehicles, so that they too pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if one aspirin is sufficient," explains Randy Rentschler, the Commission's Head of Legislation and Public Affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about their privacy and many other things.
