US-Border: "Super-Tunnel" zum Drogenschmuggel entdeckt
On the border between Mexico and the US, investigators have discovered and shut down a "super" tunnel for drug smuggling.
According to US Customs, the more than 500-meter-long pipe between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, railway tracks, and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested, eight tons of marijuana and nearly 150 kilograms of cocaine were seized.
According to the figures, the tunnel had not yet been opened.
"These cartels are stupid if they think they can dig their way under the radar," said Laura Duffy, Attorney General of Southern California District, at a press conference outside a San Diego warehouse where one end of the tunnel had been discovered.
Addressing the drug gangs, Duffy assured them: "If you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them, we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money."
Both the US authorities and the Mexican security forces are engaged in a long-term fight against the drug cartels.
Since 2006, more than 77,000 people have been killed in Mexico in connection with drug-related crime.
Designed by experts
Due to the extensive furnishing of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year.
The track system was equipped in such a way that electric cars could be used there.
On the Mexican side, the entrance is located in a building 80 meters from the border.
According to the authorities, a ladder leads 20 metres down to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross-section of 1.20 metres high and 90 centimetres wide.
It would also have been appropriate to encourage illegal immigration into the United States.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine discovery.
The third, a Mexican, was apprehended for the confiscated marijuana.
All three face life imprisonment as the maximum punishment, as officials have said.
According to the press conference in San Diego, eight such tunnels have been discovered since 2006.
However, it is the first time that cocaine has been found in such a tunnel.
Cocaine is usually smuggled in small quantities and not through tunnels.
This shows the "desperation" of the drug gangs, whose traditional routes have been cut off, said Bill Sherman of the DEA drug investigation agency in San Diego.
They would do anything to get to the US.
No details of the detainees were disclosed, at least one was Mexican, it was said.
They can expect prison sentences of up to ten years.
