Council takes aim at track systems
Should the "Am Hirschen" level crossing be extensively rebuilt to increase road safety?
Yes, the municipal councils have decided.
Schiltach has to take EUR 220 000 into its hands.
The Deutsche Bahn wants to improve the Kinzigtal in the coming year.
In particular, the safety at level crossings is to be increased - there are regular nationwide collisions of trains with other vehicles.
If the municipalities agree to the reconstruction measures, they must contribute a third of the costs, the rest is shared by the railways and the federal government.
Schiltach ’ s urban architect Roland Grießhaber explained the specifics of the railway crossing “Am Hirschen ” to the local council.
There the city plans to build a bulge west of the railway tracks at the height of the tunnel mouth there.
Larger vehicles, such as those transporting long timber, could also be parked there on oncoming traffic without having to block the tracks.
Grießhaber therefore proposed to construct a necessary retaining wall in such a way that the city could widen the adjacent street in due course in order to ensure a smooth flow of traffic.
This was discussed controversially in the municipal council, as some councils questioned the necessity of road dissemination: Thomas Kipp summed up the critics' mood with his statement: "Do we have to take so much money into our hands because of so few vehicles?"
Mayor Thomas Haas disagreed: The "Hirschen" level crossing is regularly used for transporting long timber.
Even wood from the area "Kuhbach" is partly transported on this route, because the up to 20 Meters long vehicles could not use the route at the Häberlesbrücke, because they could not turn into the main road.
Furthermore, the route serves as a diversion for those vehicles that are not allowed to use the tunnel when the main road is closed, Haas argued.
Since it could be foreseen that Kirchberg and Schlossberg tunnels would have to be rebuilt and refurbished, as is currently the case in Wolfach, the "Am" Hirschen level crossing could also have an important traffic significance for a longer period of time.
The councils agreed to have an investigation carried out into what the planned widening of the road would cost.
Regardless of this, the majority agreed to the reconstruction of the level crossing with the stipulation that the necessary retaining wall would be constructed in such a way that the city could expand the adjacent road in the direction of "Bahnhofstrasse" to around 5.5 metres, if necessary, for meeting traffic.
The reconstruction of the level crossing at the Trautwein Tannery, on the other hand, could lead to a completely different problem concerning the access road to the steeply rising "Geroltzhäuser Weg".
The administration had the plans for the reconstruction of the railway examined by the Breinlinger engineering office, as it had doubts whether the planned connection of the Geroltzhäuser Weg would still be possible without further ado.
The investigation concluded that it could not be ruled out that the gradient of the road could lead to longer vehicles being on the road.
The responsibility for this in turn lies with the city as a road load carrier.
The conversion could therefore lead to liability disputes.
Since both the timber removal and the turning worked in the current state, the reconstruction of the level crossing should not be approved, Haas argued.
Furthermore, the risk of a collision of the train with a vehicle on the crossing at this point was significantly lower than at the other level crossings, because the middle station, to which there was a good line of sight, was located directly next to it.
Even trains from the central station should be braked at this point already so far that no collision threatens.
According to the councils, the majority of the people refused to agree to the reconstruction of this level crossing, as the town of Schiltach would have to "take the brunt" of the problem with vehicles on the ground, as the railway could withdraw from responsibility after the completion of the construction work.
The committee regards as unproblematic the conversions at the level crossings "Vor Heubach" and "Vor Kuhbach", for which already crossing agreements with the railway were made.
Esa Decides on Large Space Missions: Missions for Billions
Distant planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the coming years.
30 proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far Worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1000 planets near other stars.
Whether there are lives on at least some of them, nobody knows.
The choice is difficult: Should one look for gravitational-waves?
Or rather investigate the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and discover extraterrestrial life?
Those in charge of the European Space Agency, Esa, are asking themselves these questions.
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that will make a decisive contribution to research.
The budget for such "L" missions is approximately one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were on the agenda, five of which have now been shortlisted.
Numerous bodies examine the proposals, check with the researchers.
A final decision by the Scientific Programme Committee is to be taken in the next few days.
Esa has selected a total of four major questions to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme initiated in 2007 are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to investigate this question, the space telescope "Cheops" is to be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity will be examined in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for "biomarkers": gases that are considered indicative of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to shed light on the preconditions for the emergence of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and its particle radiation with the planetary system play an important role.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated by way of example.
With the "Solar Orbiter" Esa has already approved a mission of the M ’ class (where the budget is about half a billion Euros) for this question.
The spacecraft will launch in 2017 and observe the surface and activity of the Sun closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the development of the solar system.
For this Esa provides the first of a total of three L ’ missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The spacecraft "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is scheduled to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter to study the planet ’ s atmosphere and the icy moons of Europa, Callisto, and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to examine whether the natural laws known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations, which could show the physicists the way to a new theory, under whose roof all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
Our cosmos was created by the Big Bang 13.7 billion years ago.
In addition to the matter we know, consisting of stars, planets and living beings like ourselves, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, through whose action the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", Esa has already approved an "M" mission, the start of which is scheduled for 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
In the opinion of many experts, the best chances of obtaining a permit as a L ’ mission is "E ’ Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand this to mean changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
To this day they have not been proven.
Elisa could do that, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission envisages a detector consisting of two or three probes, which will be stationed in space.
In contrast to plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that originated at the Big Bang and thus provide new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals compete for the second mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which will explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which will detect and study Earth-like planets.
Among other things, proposals have already been submitted for the samples, return transport from Mars, research on the Moon, Venus and asteroids, and solar physics.
