What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E ’ Mail is actually called electronic letter.
Was the design of the Internet Service E, Mail similar to the conventional mail implemented technically the secrecy of letters?
When designing the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not been designed to provide a stable basis for an audible exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
When user "Anna" sends an e-mail to "Benni", are the computers of the two connected directly?
The first step of the email program or Anna's browser is to send the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if she has a GMail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
On the route the mail can run over several other servers in the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are traditional e-mails read on their way through the net?
Most mails are read several times by software on the way.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also performed on the recipient ’ s systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam, which is deleted immediately or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
In systems like GMail, the robot also detects the information that Google needs to place contextual advertisements.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can show corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read the e-mails?
The probability that unauthorized persons will read an e-mail is extremely low.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read e-mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal means to intercept or take note of e-mails.
There are also possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from being read?
With OpenPGP encryption, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to disguise the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even readily possible to recognize who has communicated with whom.
