George Kerevan: European unbundling gives Scots a choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time, we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire border along Hadrian ’ s Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde proposal highlighted the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom to travel in the rest of Europe, but this did not matter in the headlines, as was expected.
Nor has anyone mentioned that the EU ’ s member states often bend their strict rules when it is more convenient for them.
As Scotland is not currently in the Schengen area, continuing to ignore it would be a small concession for Brussels in exchange for what we really want from the Scots.
So actually no story.
And one that has already grown so old that it already resembles a fossil: The first time I heard the "independence means passport control" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the European tune?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan for European unification has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project has officially died.
Throughout the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as the common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic Alternative for Germany party - founded just this year - secured just under five million votes in the general election in September, effectively evicting the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket into which each national economy is forced by adherence to the single currency, many people believe that the European project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits - only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters - and German policymakers like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of local currency depreciation, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending, spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the 'green' energy directives imposed by Brussels - a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much as the United States for electricity and four times as much for gas.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage fixes of the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, the EU ’ s one-time cheerleader.
After the war, France ’ s political elite viewed the EU as a vehicle for holding Germany in check and raising Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and has imposed its own economic policies on Europe, which the ailing French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen ’ s right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a crucial by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France, with 24% of the vote - a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that right-wing divisions will automatically benefit the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newfound popularity among white working-class French?
It would like to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-single currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections - and this is very possible - then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not-too-distant future, growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will unite to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and a few of its satellites, or economies, may cling to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of cajoling itself to the US.
But Washington ’ s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) small England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put themselves in.
I suspect that Scotland could do quite well in a looser European interconnection if we kept our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider following Norway's lead and maintaining our economic independence.
Remarkably, the SNP ’ s Scottish government is the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 over the proposed (and proposed) cuts by Labour ’ s finance minister, Alistair Darling, and the subsequent Tory Lib Dem.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to choose independence now, only to have austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
Afro-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, as research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children ’ s health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair grow at the age of seven or eight?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics ’ annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, the pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz stated that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and constituted a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents - usually this is not a sign that puberty is fast approaching," Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious indications of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Nevertheless, there was only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (occurrence of the first menstruation) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of the breasts begins, it still takes at least two to three years until the menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: the essential guide to dealing with this frequently occurring problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually represents the onset of puberty, but it is "premature" when the breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates - something that a pediatrician can monitor closely.
With faster progress, tests by an endicronologist may be indicated to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments for delaying early menstruation and preventing another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for a drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reticent about drugs, but he admits: "Suppressing puberty can ease behavioral problems and girls' feelings of being different from their peers."
The other major problem is understandable: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side," said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days at the age of ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school frightened and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many comprehensively published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys reach puberty like girls do.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the implementation of a 2001 study on girls aged 6 to 9 years, which established a link between body fat and the onset of puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys grow their facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference highlighted the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is widespread even among babies and toddlers.
"We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"That can mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
If one remains calm, the child usually reacts well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than expected.
