New nicotine vaccine could kill the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil smoking fun.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
More tests are needed before testing on humans, which may take a few years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good.
"We are very hopeful that this kind of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and tried all the methods available on the market, but have found that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches," Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information needed to produce nicotine, or antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, leaving a smoker with no nicotine.
In experiments, vaccinated mice administered nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, had taken a "time-out", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brain.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Earlier tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain the antibody level that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is safe, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thereby preventing nicotine addiction.
But smokers are more likely to use it to quit.
"They know that when they start smoking again, they no longer enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them get rid of their habit," he explains.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but warned that more research was needed.
