Pawnbrokers booming in Singapore as middle-class crisis hits
In a pawn shop in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings in order to be able to pay the school fees of her daughters.
"My husband and I have just bought a house, I put all my money in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (approx. 1,730 euros) every month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
Indeed, in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is rising – demand is so high that ValueMax, where it has made its exchange, became the third pawnbroker listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pledging jewellery is not only a quick way to get money - 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga - but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnbrokers in Singapore require an annual APR of 17%, just above the 15.4% charged by the United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnbrokers have the advantage that there is no need to check creditworthiness or income, which is why loans are possible more quickly than with banks.
As a result, millions of people in the region turn to pawnbrokers as families feel the pressure of rising living costs and household and consumer indebtedness.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit due to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, low- and middle-income families seek out pawnbrokers to make up the difference in a stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor ’ s called growing household debt, mainly through rising mortgages, a risk factor for Asian banks ’ creditworthiness.
According to the Agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia tops the list with 80% of GDP, an increase of 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which has just emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed continued export weakness and a decline in consumer demand.
“In the end, as costs rise, middle-to-lower-income people will try to supplement their income wherever possible, ” says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical peaks in gold prices over the past two years have amplified the trend toward mortgaging personal belongings, as people seize the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged objects in the 200 pawnbrokers of the city-state are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pledge grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20 percent increase in customer numbers in its stores in recent months.
ValueMax, which operates the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, will not only expand into neighboring Malaysia – where it operates four stores – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, ValueMax ’ s Managing Director.
The company is funding it with 60 percent of Singapore ’ s $66 million that it earned this week with its IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire over high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnbrokers not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
"Customers lend items they already own, and liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase household debt," she explains.
The pawn loan business is increasingly socially accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawnshops are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
“These include wealthy people who borrow for business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks, ” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
