Rescue package of 325 million Australian dollars for Tasmanian healthcare
The Australian government insists on the tough conditions attached to the $325 million Australian health bailout package to ensure that the state government cannot waste the money.
Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek has announced that the Commonwealth will take "immediate measures" to avert a crisis caused by an aging population of the island state, a higher rate of chronic diseases and system restrictions.
The financing for a period of four years was decided after government consultations with the independent Tasmanian deputy Andrew Wilkie.
"The government has put together an emergency rescue package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state," Plibersek said today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency electoral assistance.
A further 2,600 operations, including orthopaedic procedures and treatments for cataracts, are intended to remove residues.
There is also money for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better post-hospital care, specialist training, mental health services, and the introduction of an electronic health record system in local hospitals.
"These investments are in line with the ideas that affected hospital staff have told me are the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system," said Tanya Plibersek.
The Minister insisted on strict reporting and accountability by the Tasmanian Government.
The state must maintain the current level of funding to receive money from the Commonwealth and report monthly on where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member commission will be established to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie said today, the $325 million would be of little use if "it is not accompanied by real reforms that put Tasmania's public health system on a more sustainable path."
Nevertheless, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent assistance, which he first expressed to the Prime Minister at the beginning of May.
“I am confident that federal aid will make a major contribution to removing the state ’ s public health system from the list of concerns, ” Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these electoral benefits will largely offset the recent cuts.
But Peter Dutton, the opposition's health spokesman at the federal level, believes that today's announcement is only a "plaster solution."
"We are in the current situation because the labor state government has withdrawn 430 million dollars from the health system," he told ABC TV.
It is not acceptable for a state government to take nearly half a billion dollars out of the system and put 300 million into the Commonwealth and then pretend that this is good news.
Dutton called on Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
