Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed important facilities for the production of chemical weapons and lattice gas ammunition, said the Global Monitoring Group on Chemical Weapons on Thursday, while in the north of the country there were serious clashes near one of the sites where toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people have been killed since the beginning of the civil war three years ago.
The announcement made by the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came one day before the
1 November, which the Damascus-based organization in The Hague had set to destroy or render "inoperable" all facilities for the production of chemical weapons, including all machinery for mixing chemicals into poison gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is essentially the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all of Syria ’ s chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
But Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and stockpiles.
According to assumptions, there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting was taking place on Thursday in the city of Safira, where experts say there is a production facility for chemical weapons and storage facilities, according to the British-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
The activist group, which is monitoring the number of deaths through a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them were members of President Bashar Assad ’ s army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters, and 187 were Lebanese Hezbollah militants.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the number of deaths in the conflict at 100,000 since March 2011.
This figure has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad ’ s forces have been fighting for weeks in Safira against the rebels, many of whom have ties to al Qaeda ’ s groups.
The observatory said there had been losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not give any details.
The fighting underscores the danger to which the chemical weapons inspectors are exposed, because their mission to free Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team is "now convinced that it has seen and experienced the destruction of all the important production and mixing / filling facilities mentioned by Syria."
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 of the 23 sites reported by Damascus.
The inspectors said that due to security concerns it was not possible to visit two facilities.
On Thursday, the OPWC said that, according to Syrian sources, the two sites had been "abandoned... and the chemical weapons program facilities there had been moved to other facilities that had been inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has put forward a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, to be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
"I salute the bravery and courage you have all shown in carrying out the most challenging mission ever undertaken by this organization," said Ahmed Uzumcu, Director General of the Monitoring Organization, in a commentary published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels in this civil war have been fighting against Assad ’ s government and its security forces, to which many members of the Alawites belong, a secession of Shia Islam.
Regarding further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said that on Wednesday there had been a strong explosion at an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion was unknown, he explained.
Anger at Judgment for Bali Bombers
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people killed in the Bali bombing in 2002 reacted angrily to the verdict of the last of the instigators, who were brought to justice because they believed that Umar Patek should be shot.
Patek, who has been on the run for almost ten years as one of the most wanted people in Southeast Asia, was sentenced to 20 years in prison yesterday for his role in building explosives for the bomb attack.
He could be released after 15 years with a stay.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of mass murder for attacking two nightclubs in the popular tourist area of Kuta, killing 202 people, including 88 Australians, and injuring many more.
A conviction was also handed down on a number of terrorist charges, including a wave of explosives attacks on churches in Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
The prosecution had demanded a life sentence, even if it could have applied for the death penalty for the man, who is also called "Demolition Man" because of his reputation as a master bomb builder.
The decision has awakened painful memories of June Corteen, a mother from Perth who lost her 39-year-old twin daughters Jane and Jenny in the devastation wrought by Patek and his co-conspirators nearly ten years ago.
Fighting in tears, she said that Patek should have been sentenced to death.
I really mean he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
"You should put him in front of a firing squad," Corteen told AAP.
Every day I have to live with the fact that I will not have any more grandchildren and I will never see my daughters again.
The Sari Club was razed to the ground when on October 12, 2002, shortly after 11 p.m., a huge bomb exploded in a small truck parked in front of the nightclub.
Peter Hughes was in Paddy's Bar, where only 20 seconds earlier a suicide bomber exploded a backpack filled with explosives.
He fell into a coma for a month after the attack and "died" three times while attached to a life-support system.
Hughes said that Patek deserved the same fate as the three other members of the Jemaah Islamiah terrorist cell - Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra - who were responsible for the bloodbath and were executed four years ago.
Really, this guy should get the death penalty before anyone else.
To keep him alive - no, there is no reason to keep him alive.
Getting 20 years after killing 202 people and injuring many hundreds is not much.
Patek is the last of Bali ’ s legal bombers.
He escaped arrest for nearly a decade, but was eventually apprehended in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where US forces killed former al Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden barely four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that intelligence reports had revealed that Patek was in Pakistan to meet bin Laden with the aim of reconnecting Southeast Asian terrorist groups with al Qaeda.
"He didn't stand," Corteen said.
Until recently, he has shown no remorse for how much suffering he has caused to other people.
The verdict comes before the tenth anniversary of the attack this year, which is commemorated with commemorations in Bali and Australia.
"There will be many tears this year," said Corteen.
Patek can still appeal his verdict.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but not make mobile phone calls)
From departure to landing, passengers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play games, listen to music and watch films, but not to use their mobile phones, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the USA on Thursday.
But passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented would depend on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines will have to demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new Directives and that they have updated the training manuals for flight staff and the rules for stowing equipment in line with the new rules.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were also Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to switch off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not take off again until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the approach, passengers must switch them off again and must not take off again until the aircraft has landed.
According to the new directives, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use the equipment during take-off, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most of the new commercial aircraft and other planes that have been modified for the use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Flight Attendants Association, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regulation is implemented safely - and we are working closely with the airline on this - both sides will benefit," Glading commented.
To be honest, we are tired of feeling like watchdogs on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to publicly leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, must continue to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight also remain forbidden.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert on CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we at FCC know that transmission from the air can also disrupt transmitter towers," says Rosenker.
Last month, an industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA to ease restrictions on use has increased.
Critics such as Missouri ’ s Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of equipment has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is said that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore switching off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travellers in 1966, after reports of disruptions to navigation and communication equipment caused by airborne VHF radios became known, representing the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that they do not mind electronic interference.
For some years now, airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi when the flight altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to WiFi-systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for increased use of electronic devices under the new directives, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
A reader, for example, only emits minimal radiation when turning pages.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Proponents of loosening restrictions on passenger use include Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle E-readers and made a test flight to determine problems, but could not determine any.
Members of the FAA ’ s Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed that the equipment was causing real disruption, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there were only occasional reports of pilots arguing for aircraft systems to be disrupted by the equipment, and most of them were very old.
The committee, however, recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the passengers to switch off the equipment when instruments are landed in poor visibility.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a sensible adjustment for travellers who would be well equipped with technology today.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience does not contradict safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
