Is Europe ’ s elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the aim of bringing the economy around the table and defining what those who provide wealth and work in Britain want to change in our relations with the EU.
To that end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders, asking them what they think about Britain, the economy, and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders, who roughly represent the UK ’ s corporate sizes, sectors, and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside Europe and concentrating on countries that are modernising and growing while the EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to favor new trade links with countries like China, India, and Brazil, rather than embarking on the long and arduous process of reforming obscure EU institutions.
When asked about their views on certain statutory issues – from antitrust to product legislation – the majority of business leaders believe that control over these key competences should be brought back to Westminster.
There was widespread dissatisfaction with the Internal Market, because, according to companies, the costs of the Brussels rules would outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe's trading zone - even 40% of large companies, which are traditionally the most pro-European, agreed.
Finally, and probably most importantly, our questioning of business leaders revealed that a clear majority of the UK wants a course towards changing the deal and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This finding, which can be found in companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a "meaningful change" that will bring the lever of action back to Great Britain.
There is much at stake - a change to the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a 16% change of opinion in favour of remaining in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that the British economy is behind his plan to renegotiate Britain ’ s terms for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a significant shift in the balance of power back to Britain from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible, and increasingly necessary, as the eurozone moves toward closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the results of our survey show, which means increased attention to trade for businesses and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulation.
