Scientists were able to shed more light on the relationship between the tail wagging of a dog and its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog ’ s point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres react differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this with other species.
He also noticed that in dogs, just as in humans, the right brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in feelings.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the waving tails of their conspecifics, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the dogs and analysed their behaviour.
Probably we will understand soon, why the tail moves sometimes in one, sometimes in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs films with dogs - either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw how an otherwise inexpressive dog moved its tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not communicate intentionally with each other through these movements.
He is rather convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience, with which movements they should worry and when not.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wagging with the tail in one direction is more connected with friendly behavior and the right side rather produces a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animal.
John Bradshaw, a dog behaviour expert and guest fellow at the University of Bristol Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria, Canada, the following was stated: "Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when its' tail 'waves to the left and not to the right, rather than becoming restless - exactly the other way around than in the Italian study."
According to his statement, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined – and dogs are no exception, ” Bradshaw said.
Since their behaviour can be easily recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
