Pope Francis Appoints First Cardinals in February
Pope Francis will on 22 February for the first time appoint new cardinals of the Catholic Church, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the most senior clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a Pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer participate in the papal election - this belongs to a group of 120 "cardinals entitled to vote".
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, spokesman for the Vatican, said that there would be a meeting of all the cardinals before the ceremony to nominate the new cardinals, also known as the consistory, would be held.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the Consistory in February in advance, so that other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that the number of cardinals eligible to vote would probably have fallen by February.
He said that a Pope normally appoints as many cardinals as necessary to restore the number of cardinals eligible to vote to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he desires.
According to Valero, the Consistory next year is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March of this year.
At the moment, there is a certain overhang on the part of Europe, particularly Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be called, since the creation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight Cardinals from all over the world, charged with finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything by himself.
“Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him, ” Valero said.
He said it was "quite possible" that Francis asked the cardinals for advice.
