Obama ’ s cry of despair
I elected President Obama twice in the hope that change was possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by the Republican blockade tactics
The blockade policy doesn ’ t excuse the Obamacare website ’ s trouble making drone strikes
Obama's memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what might have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It is a book that I thought would cheer me up and give me hope during the gloomy second year of my medical studies.
It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes Barack Obama's memoirs on the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient transcripts in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take one ’ s breath away.
The election became a landslide victory, and news spokesmen paused to recall the historic significance of the moment.
My classmates cried with joy, and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a nasty awakening, like being ripped out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these optimistic times - they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first voted, things have indeed changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I acknowledge the great and diverse things that Obama has achieved, from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the army ’ s forced concealment of homosexuality, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I agree that the party-political blockade tactic has overturned too many of the efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name but a few.
But, having defended the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end of my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican blockade cannot explain why foreign leaders are allowed to be intercepted or innocent children killed by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on Americans ’ private lives, and why whistleblowers who expose government misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits were circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the findings of a report that says the White House's efforts to immobilize the media are "the most aggressive... since the Nixon administration."
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that the work of government could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the legislature is not a predictable course of action, as an opposition party and accidental events like the Newtown Massacre are shaping public debate.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a bewildering and half-baked alternative; he seemed incapable of determining his direction and positions.
It seemed to me that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope that we had long heard about.
But, with Obama ’ s approval rating falling below 45% this week, the book has made the return to 2008 all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week, I read a section in the book describing how Obama suffered a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primaries.
In a meeting with the election officials after the decision, he told his staff that they had to get back on track and follow the purpose of their case.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
We must remember who we are.
It is five years later, Mr President, and I could not agree more with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
