RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange department, according to two people familiar with the situation, another indication that the global regulatory investigation into alleged manipulation of the currency market is gathering speed.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with the authorities in investigations in the world's largest financial market, where 5.3 trillion US dollars change hands every day.
The two traders would be the first RBS employees to be suspended in the expanding investigation into the Libor ’ s interbank business scandal.
The bank, which did not comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from the authorities.
"Our investigation on this issue continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators," the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people close to the situation indicated that RBS had forwarded the recordings of e-mails and instant messages sent by and to a former trader to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, had left RBS in 2010 and is said to have been suspended from his current position as European head of the Forex Spot, Trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European Spot Trading at Citi, was on leave this week and Matt Gardiner, former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended this week at Standard Chartered.
