At least six authorities worldwide - the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are currently dealing with allegations that bankers have colluded in transactions on the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from authorities, said people familiar with the situation.
Banks comb through instant messages and emails from several years in search of cases of misconduct.
The news of these investigations has thrown traders into turmoil in an area that has been one of the most profitable trading units of investment banks in recent years, but this year has been under pressure because low currency volatility is limiting opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the affair, saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast and highly liquid foreign exchange market, but leading traders believe that this is not necessarily true.
A leading trader noted that despite the enormous daily volume of forex trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the increasing use of their own internal platforms by banks means that "even with a very small ticket, you can influence the market".
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had fired a trader from its London Exchange Traded Fund office this week after causing a loss of nearly $6 million at the end of last year.
