On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle belongs to the Top 10 of "CNN Heroes of 2013".
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the Top 10 to be voted "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner will receive 250,000 dollars to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father lost consciousness and travelled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation developed that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma there that would affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
One can leave the house at five o'clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, but is not the first.
There are many patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle ’ s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organisation, there is only one doctor in Cameroon for every 5,000 people.
In the United States, on the other hand, the ratio is that of a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two in five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty, ” says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffering made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team conducted 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon in the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and drive with the tied up medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Everything does not always run smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation that the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and Bwelle - with his broad smile and his boundless energy - is happy to take part in the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team starts examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village - on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document that is required for school but that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening the team performs simple operations with local anaesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, a town hall or a flat; after the surgery the patients get up and go to the relaxation area to make room for their neighbour.
The lighting for the operating room and the disinfection equipment is supplied by the generator of the group and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It is an exhausting workload, but the village musicians usually help to keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so that we can stay awake and continue our work, ” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group - a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students - carried out 700 free surgeries last year and knows that its work makes a huge difference for the people it helps.
A man explained that the free hernia operation he had received now enabled him to return to work.
"That changes the future of my family," said the man.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his charitable activity, so Bwelle; the remainder comes from private donations.
“I really don ’ t know when he ’ s sleeping, ” says Katie O ’ Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteer in Bwelles Group.
He is always either in hospital or trying to raise money for the organisation so that he can take part in these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
"We can be involved in operations where we help to tap blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon and often bring medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, the transport and the instruction.
"He is without a doubt a hero," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organisation and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to a happier life and fulfilling a promise he made to his father gives him great joy.
"I am so happy when I do this work," says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I am doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
