Tourism: descent to the Romans
A sewer from the Roman era has been preserved at a length of around 120 metres below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you can't miss the cathedral.
The two towers rise about 157 metres into the sky and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree church towers, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his tours is the Service Center of Cologne Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park", says Schulze.
In the seventies the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only that which was not too big remained of the remains of the old city walls.
Most of today ’ s users of the car park therefore hurry past the Roman remains and just park their car.
But who looks more closely, discovers in the parking deck D2 an archaeological place of discovery separated by metal lattice bars.
You can see about five meters high ruins made of palm-sized stones.
"These are remnants of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century AD," says Schulze.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look into a dark shaft 15 meters deep.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately also hardly noticed.
The next station of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend into the depths again.
Here we experience the official seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the President of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for" Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium ", which in good German means" city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinensians, founded under the Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the emperor cult ".
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
A tunnel access leads from the antechamber of the exhibition to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at a length of around 120 metres.
"You can quietly walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze encouraged the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After fetching the key from the cash register, he leads the group to a 16 metre deep, accessible shaft.
"We are now in the mikvah, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground in order to get the groundwater that was indispensable for the ritual ablutions.
Until today, in the lower end of the mikveh, whose origins go back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing gauges of the Rhine.
The mikveh will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
But it will take a few years to complete.
